{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d1bb2c6e-2ea5-4ea3-a15d-5d73bcedd707","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — For additional context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 5m\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48ca7d0c-b7ba-48f6-b18d-79568bcf2534","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":311,"requestId":"D816:1E62:2987348:2DDF17D:69FBF029"},"id":"2f718f33-3527-4b11-b0ba-330d4589b932","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:50.412Z","parentId":"656228fd-a1da-4228-8a96-830096ea9291"}
